        "title": "Chapter 1: The Anatomy of Rejection (1/23)",
        "content": "<p>The humidity wakes him before the heat does.</p><p>It sits on Bobi&#39;s chest like a hand \u2014 warm, damp, insistent. The air in the room has weight. It presses against his closed eyelids, pools in the hollows of his collarbones, settles in the crease behind his knees where the thin sheet has twisted and abandoned him sometime in the night. Manado&#39;s equatorial morning doesn&#39;t announce itself with light first. It announces itself with wet.</p><p>He lies still. Eyes closed. Mattress foam beneath him compressed to the density of old bread, damp with sweat that is his and also the room&#39;s \u2014 the accumulated moisture of a space that has no air conditioning, no cross-breeze, only the tin roof conducting heat downward like a lid on a pot. The pillowcase smells like his scalp. Sour. Organic. The particular geography of a bald man&#39;s head in a climate that has no mercy for exposed skin.</p><p>Before he opens his eyes, he takes inventory.</p><p>The scalp first. Always the scalp. He can feel it without touching \u2014 the nakedness of it, the vulnerability. A surface that should be covered and isn&#39;t. Genetics as cruelty. His mother&#39;s father was bald. His mother&#39;s brother was bald. The village aunts used to say <em>it skips a generation</em>, but they were wrong. It didn&#39;t skip. It landed. On him. Not on his brother. Never on his brother.</p><p>He can feel where the sweat has pooled at his hairline \u2014 or what would be his hairline if he had one. The phantom border where follicles surrendered years ago, leaving only the gleaming dome that flushes pink in heat, red in shame, mottled brown-pink when he&#39;s anxious. Which is always. The scalp is a mood ring he cannot hide. A broadcast system for every emotion he would prefer to keep internal.</p><p>His nose next. The <em>hidung kampung</em> \u2014 village nose. Wide. Flat. The bridge low, the nostrils flared. His brother&#39;s nose was different. Narrower. The aunts said <em>distinguished</em>. They said <em>takes after father&#39;s side</em>. They never said what Bobi&#39;s nose took after. They didn&#39;t have to. <em>Si jelek</em> takes after the recessive traits, the genetic errors, the rough drafts that should have been crumpled and thrown away before the final copy emerged.</p><p>The jawline. Soft. He can feel the way his face meets his neck without the hard angle that marks a man&#39;s face as <em>strong</em>, as <em>carved</em>, as anything other than unfinished. His jaw is clay that never hardened in the kiln. His brother&#39;s jaw was stone. Bobi&#39;s is something that would yield under pressure, give way, collapse inward if you pressed hard enough.</p><p>The skin. Porous. He doesn&#39;t need to see it to know its texture. Even with his eyes closed, lying in the accumulated damp of his own night sweat, he can feel the size of the pores on his cheeks, his forehead, the sides of his nose. Craters. Moon surface. The acne of adolescence is gone, but the evidence remains \u2014 a topographic map of every infection, every squeeze, every attempt to extract the ugliness one whitehead at a time. His brother&#39;s skin was smooth. The village girls said <em>porcelain</em>. They never touched Bobi&#39;s face to compare.</p><p>He has been awake for two minutes. He has not yet opened his eyes. Already the debt is compounding.</p>"
