        "chapter": 1,
        "isChapterStart": false,
        "title": "Chapter 1: The Anatomy of Rejection (2/23)",
        "content": "<p>The genetic debt. <em>Hutang genetik</em> \u2014 if he were to name it in Indonesian, though he doesn&#39;t, not even in his thoughts, because naming it would make it too real, too specific, a thing that could be negotiated or disputed. Better to leave it as a weight. As an obligation without terms. A debt owed to the universe for the crime of being born second, born wrong, born as the mistake that the genes corrected thirty seconds later when his brother emerged.</p><p>Identical twins. That&#39;s what the village called them. <em>Kembar identik</em>. But the village was lying, or blind, or kind in the way that makes cruelty worse \u2014 pretending not to see the obvious hierarchy. One beautiful. One not. One kissed first by the aunts at every gathering. One kissed second, after the lips had cooled, after the affection had already been spent on the better version.</p><p><em>Si jelek.</em> The ugly one.</p><p>He heard it first when he was six. Maybe seven. A birthday party \u2014 his? His brother&#39;s? Both, probably, because twins share everything except the distribution of beauty. The long table under the blue tarp in the front yard of the family compound. The uncles drinking <em>Cap Tikus</em>. The aunts bringing out the <em>babi putar</em>, the whole roasted pig that meant this was a real celebration. And two boys in matching shirts \u2014 his mother liked to dress them the same, as if clothing could erase what the genes had written differently on their faces.</p><p>The aunts descended. They always descended in a flock, a cluster of floral prints and lipstick and the particular fragrance of middle-aged women in a Christian Minahasan village \u2014 something between jasmine and mothballs and the faint petroleum smell of pressed powder. They kissed his brother first. They always kissed his brother first.</p><p>Then they turned to Bobi. And one of them \u2014 he doesn&#39;t remember which aunt, they blurred together in his memory like a single organism with multiple mouths \u2014 leaned down and kissed his cheek, and as she pulled away, she whispered to the aunt beside her. Not a whisper meant to be private. A whisper meant to be overheard by the child whose face was still wet from her lipstick.</p><p><em>&quot;Si jelek.&quot;</em></p><p>The ugly one.</p><p>Not an insult. Not even unkind, in her mind. Just an identification. A taxonomy. A way to tell them apart when their names were too similar and their clothes were identical and the only reliable difference was the one written in bone structure and skin quality and the particular arrangement of features that the universe had distributed unequally between two bodies that were supposed to be the same.</p><p>He didn&#39;t cry. He learned early that crying about ugliness only confirmed it. Ugly boys who cry become uglier. The salt tracks on the cheeks. The red eyes. The swollen nose. Every tear is evidence.</p>"
