        "chapter": 1,
        "isChapterStart": false,
        "title": "Chapter 1: The Anatomy of Rejection (3/23)",
        "content": "<p>He learned to laugh instead. The village laugh. Mouth wide. All teeth showing. Cheeks pushed up until his eyes narrowed to slits. The laugh that means <em>I am in on the joke</em>. The laugh that means <em>you cannot hurt me because I am already laughing at myself</em>. The laugh that costs nothing to produce and protects everything it needs to protect, which is not the body \u2014 the body is indefensible \u2014 but the small part of the self that still believes it deserves to be here.</p><p>He perfected that laugh by the time he was ten. By fifteen, it was automatic. By twenty, it was the only expression his face made in public. Now, at thirty-one, lying on a damp mattress in a rented room in Manado city, two hours by car from the village he will never return to, the laugh is still there. Waiting. Ready to deploy the moment anyone looks at him long enough to make a judgment.</p><p>But here, alone, eyes still closed, he doesn&#39;t have to laugh.</p><p>Here, he can simply owe.</p><p>The fluorescent tube overhead buzzes. It has been buzzing since he woke, but he&#39;s only noticing it now, the way you notice tinnitus only when you think about it. The buzz is uneven \u2014 not a clean hum but something arrhythmic, struggling, a light that is trying to die but hasn&#39;t been given permission. The sound is the frequency of God thinking about giving up. He read that phrase somewhere once, on some website in some language he barely understood, and it stuck. The fluorescent buzz as divine exhaustion. It felt true.</p><p>He opens his eyes.</p><p>The ceiling is there. The water stains spread across the white paint like continents on a map of a world no one would want to visit. Brown archipelagos. Yellow estuaries. The paint has bubbled in places where the humidity has worked its way between the concrete and the coating, creating topographies that Bobi sometimes traces with his eyes when he can&#39;t sleep, reading them like braille instructions for a procedure he hasn&#39;t yet attempted.</p><p>The room smells like it always smells. Clove cigarettes \u2014 <em>kretek</em>, the Gudang Garam Surya brand in the red pack, the ones that are more clove than tobacco and leave a sweet, medicinal residue in the lungs. He doesn&#39;t smoke as much as he used to. His mouth tastes wrong lately. But the smell is embedded in the mattress foam, the thin curtain, the walls. It is the smell of every Indonesian man who has ever rented a cheap room and tried to fill it with something other than his own thoughts.</p><p>Beneath the clove smoke: mildew. The green-black blooms in the corners where the walls meet the ceiling, the colonies that grow faster than he can wipe them away with a rag soaked in bleach-water. The mildew is Manado&#39;s signature. Coastal humidity plus equatorial heat plus poor ventilation equals a room that is always slightly alive with things that shouldn&#39;t be growing indoors.</p><p>And beneath that: himself. The particular smell of a body that sweats in its sleep, that doesn&#39;t shower every day because the shared bathroom down the hall is too public and the <em>bak mandi</em> water is too cold and too green and facing his own reflection in that cracked mirror at 6 a.m. is more than he can manage before the first <em>Cap Tikus</em> of the day.</p>"
