        "title": "Chapter 1: The Anatomy of Rejection (6/23)",
        "content": "<p>The door swings inward on hinges that scream. Metal on metal, no oil, the sound of things that have been opening and closing for too long without maintenance. Inside, the fluorescent tube flickers twice before committing to its sickly greenish light. This is not the warm fluorescent of his room. This is morgue-light. Autopsy-light. The kind of illumination that makes living skin look like it&#39;s already given up.</p><p>The bathroom is tiled floor to ceiling in small white squares, most of them cracked or missing. The grout has gone black with mold. In the corner sits the <em>bak mandi</em> \u2014 a concrete basin large enough to crouch in, filled with water from the tap that runs only between 5 a.m. and 7 a.m. The water is greenish today. Algae has begun its slow colonization. A plastic dipper floats on the surface.</p><p>Above the concrete sink, a mirror. Rectangular. Spotted with age, the silver backing degrading in archipelagos around the edges. Cracked \u2014 a single diagonal line running from the upper left to the lower right.</p><p>Bobi stands before it.</p><p>The fluorescent light touches his scalp first. The bald expanse catches the greenish glow and throws it back, oily, damp, a surface that should not be this visible. His face beneath the scalp is wide, flat, the features pressed outward as if the bones didn&#39;t have enough forward projection and had to compromise by spreading horizontally.</p><p>The nose \u2014 <em>hidung kampung</em>, village nose \u2014 broad at the bridge, the nostrils flared, the tip bulbous. Not the narrow, elegant architecture of the faces he sees on screen. Not Eline&#39;s delicate slope. Not Kyle&#39;s blade-straight line. Just wide. Present. Taking up space that could have been distributed better.</p><p>The jaw is worse. Soft. No angle. The mandible curves where it should cut. When he clenches his teeth, there is no sharp definition, just a thickening beneath the skin, a suggestion of bone that never commits. Feminine, he thinks. Weak. The kind of jaw that says: <em>This man will not protect you. This man will fold.</em></p><p>The skin is porous. Not smooth like marble or river stone. Not the matte perfection he sees in Eline&#39;s screenshots, the skin that seems to have no texture at all, just color and light. His skin has <em>geography</em>. Pores like craters. Scars from adolescent acne that he picked at for years, trying to extract the ugliness one pustule at a time, learning too late that the scars were worse than the pimples, that he had been excavating his own face and leaving mines.</p><p>The color is uneven. Darker on the cheeks where the sun hits during his rare supply runs. Paler under the jaw where shadows protect. A flush of red across the nose and forehead \u2014 broken capillaries, or the constant low-grade inflammation of skin that is too oily and too dry at the same time, skin that has given up trying to regulate itself and simply reacts.</p><p>Porous leather. That&#39;s what it looks like. The kind of leather that wasn&#39;t properly tanned, that retained too much of its organic origins, that still remembers it was once skin on a living animal and is now skin on a dying man.</p>"
