        "title": "Chapter 1: The Anatomy of Rejection (7/23)",
        "content": "<p>He opens the small cabinet above the sink. Inside: a dull razor, the kind with a single blade that costs 5,000 rupiah at the <em>warung</em>. A half-empty bottle of Betadine \u2014 brown iodine, antiseptic, the smell of every Indonesian clinic and hospital and back-alley medical procedure. A small bar of soap that has cracked from humidity.</p><p>He takes the razor.</p><p>His scalp is already bald. He does not need to shave. There is no hair to remove. But he shaves anyway. Every morning. The dull blade dragged across the naked scalp in slow, deliberate strokes, removing nothing, abrading everything.</p><p>He does not use water. He does not use soap. Just the blade on skin, dry, the friction described in sound: a low rasp, like sandpaper on soft wood.</p><p>The razor catches on a ridge of scar tissue near his crown \u2014 an old wound from childhood, falling against a concrete step, the blood in his eyes before he understood that heads bleed more than other places. The blade snags. Pulls. The skin beneath tears.</p><p>Blood.</p><p>Immediate. A bead that swells and breaks and runs. Warm. The temperature of his own body, which is always warmer than he thinks it should be, as if the fever of transformation has already begun and his thermometer simply hasn&#39;t caught up.</p><p>He does not flinch. This is routine. The blood runs down the curve of his skull, following the path of least resistance, tracking toward his temple. He watches it in the mirror. Red against the oily brown of his scalp. Bright. Almost beautiful.</p><p>He continues shaving.</p><p>Another stroke. Another catch. Another bead. The blood multiplies. Small red tributaries mapping his scalp. He is drawing a river system on his own head, a topography of violence so minor that it barely qualifies as violence, so routine that it is simply <em>maintenance</em>.</p>"
