        "title": "Chapter 1: The Anatomy of Rejection (8/23)",
        "content": "<p>The fluorescent light makes the blood look darker than it is. More brown than red. Old blood before it has finished being new blood. The greenish cast of the light sucks the life from every color.</p><p>He finishes. Sets the razor on the edge of the sink. It is slick with blood and oil. He does not rinse it. He will use it again tomorrow.</p><p>He examines his work in the mirror.</p><p>The scalp is abraded. Raw in patches. The bead-trails of blood are already drying, going tacky, darkening. He looks like a man who has been gently attacked. A man who has been told by the universe: <em>You are too soft. Let me toughen you.</em></p><p>He picks up the Betadine.</p><p>The bottle is cool. Plastic. The liquid inside sloshes \u2014 thick, viscous, the texture of cough syrup. He unscrews the cap. The smell arrives before the liquid touches skin: sweet, medicinal, chemical. The smell of every wound he has ever tried to prevent from becoming infected. The smell of care that is also violence.</p><p>He tilts the bottle. The liquid pours onto his palm. Brown. Concentrated. He rubs his palms together, warming it, distributing it.</p><p>Then he presses his hands to his scalp.</p><p>The sting is immediate. Sharp. The iodine finding every micro-abrasion, every point where the razor broke the surface, every pore that has been stretched too wide by heat and humidity. The sting is a voice that says: <em>Here. And here. And here. You are open. You are permeable. You are insufficient.</em></p><p>He massages the Betadine into his scalp with slow, circular motions. A priest anointing. A surgeon prepping a surgical field. A man performing the only ritual he has left \u2014 the ritual of acknowledgment. <em>I am damaged. I am addressing the damage. I am doing what can be done with what I have.</em></p>"
