        "title": "Chapter 1: The Anatomy of Rejection (9/23)",
        "content": "<p>The Betadine runs. Down his forehead. Into his eyebrows. Dripping onto the bridge of his nose \u2014 the <em>hidung kampung</em> that catches it and channels it toward his nostrils. He tastes it at the back of his throat. Sweet. Chemical. Wrong.</p><p>He does not stop. He covers every inch of his scalp. The crown. The temples. The base where the skull meets the neck. The Betadine turns his scalp from brown-pink to brown-amber, a color that is neither skin nor not-skin, a color that suggests he is being preserved rather than healed.</p><p>He lowers his hands. They are stained. Brown up to the wrists. He looks like a man who has been handling old blood, or rust, or the earth after a flood.</p><p>He examines his face in the mirror.</p><p>The crack in the glass runs through his left eye, splitting his face into two misaligned halves. The right side is whole. The left side is displaced, half an inch lower, as if the face has slipped on its foundation.</p><p>Two faces. One body. The rough draft and the... what? There is no final draft. There is only this. This porous leather. This wide nose. This soft jaw. This scalp that weeps Betadine and blood in equal measure.</p><p>He blinks.</p><p>And in the periphery \u2014 in the section of mirror behind him, visible over his left shoulder \u2014 something moves.</p><p>A shape. Tall. Still. Standing in the doorway of the bathroom, or just outside it, or in the hallway, or in his mind.</p><p>He does not turn.</p>"
