        "chapter": 1,
        "isChapterStart": false,
        "title": "Chapter 1: The Anatomy of Rejection (12/23)",
        "content": "<p>The smell: earth after rain. Wood smoke. Roasting pork. The particular sweetness of <em>dabu-dabu</em> \u2014 chilies and tomatoes and shallots crushed together with lime. And beneath it all, the sulfur from the hot springs two kilometers away, a smell like God&#39;s own breath after he&#39;s eaten something that disagreed with him.</p><p>Bobi stands in his room. The door is bolted. The fluorescent tube hums. The laptop sits closed on the desk. The Brother&#39;s corner is dark.</p><p>But the village is here anyway.</p><p>It arrives uninvited. It always does. A scent. A sound. A particular quality of light through the louvered window \u2014 gold and warm and <em>wrong</em> because it reminds him of <em>then</em> and he lives in <em>now</em> and the two should not touch.</p><p>But they do.</p><p>He was eight. Or nine. The age when children are still exhibited at gatherings like accomplishments, when aunts and uncles feel entitled to touch your face and proclaim judgments about your future based on the width of your nose or the darkness of your skin.</p><p>A <em>pengucapan syukur</em>. A thanksgiving. Someone&#39;s business had prospered. Someone&#39;s child had graduated. Someone had survived something that should have killed them. The reason didn&#39;t matter. What mattered was the gathering. The long table under the blue tarp strung between coconut palms. The folding chairs. The <em>kolintang</em> music from someone&#39;s phone speaker. The <em>babi putar</em> \u2014 whole roast pig \u2014 turning on the spit, fat dripping into the fire and hissing into smoke.</p><p>The compound was full. Cousins everywhere. Aunts in their Sunday clothes even though it was Saturday. Uncles smoking <em>kretek</em> in the shade. His mother moving between the outdoor kitchen and the table, carrying dishes, her face flushed from heat and pride because her twins were there and everyone would see.</p><p><em>Kembar</em>. Twin. The word followed them everywhere.</p><p>He stood beside his brother in front of the wardrobe mirror in the main room of the house. The mirror was old, spotted with black decay at the edges where the silver backing had oxidized. Their reflections were clear in the center. Identical heights. Identical builds. Identical faces.</p>"
