        "content": "<p>Then she turned to Bobi.</p><p>The same kisses. Right cheek. Left cheek. But different. Cooler. Faster. The <em>mmm</em> was absent. Her lips touched his skin where they had just touched his brother&#39;s, and he felt the residue \u2014 the wetness that was already cooling, the warmth that was already his brother&#39;s warmth and not his own.</p><p>Second kiss. Secondhand kiss.</p><p>The second aunt \u2014 Tante Mercy \u2014 did the same. Brother first. Then Bobi. The pattern established.</p><p>The third aunt \u2014 Tante Olga, the youngest of the three, the one who spoke the most and thought the least \u2014 didn&#39;t even pretend.</p><p>She kissed the brother. Both cheeks. Then she looked at Bobi and <em>patted his head</em>. A pat. Not a kiss. A gesture you give to a dog that is well-behaved but unremarkable.</p><p>&quot;<em>Kembar,</em>&quot; she said. But the word had changed shape in her mouth. It was no longer a neutral descriptor. It was a comparison. A measurement. A verdict.</p><p>She turned to his mother, who was standing in the doorway with a dish of <em>tinutuan</em> in her hands. &quot;They really are identical, <em>sa</em>? I mean, you can tell them apart, but from far away...&quot; She laughed. The laugh was high and sharp, like a bird startled from a branch.</p><p>His mother smiled. The smile was tired. &quot;They are both handsome, Tante.&quot;</p><p>&quot;<em>Iyo, iyo.</em>&quot; Yes, yes. But the agreement was hollow. The aunts exchanged a glance. A glance that said: <em>You know which one. We know which one. Everyone knows which one.</em></p>"
