        "title": "Chapter 1: The Anatomy of Rejection (17/23)",
        "content": "<p>There. The nose. His brother&#39;s nose was \u2014 what? Narrower? Straighter? Or was it the same nose, and Bobi&#39;s just looked different because he was looking at it from the inside, through the architecture of his own skull?</p><p>There. The smile. His brother smiled without effort. Bobi&#39;s smile required assembly \u2014 corners of the mouth lifted, teeth revealed, cheeks pushed up. A construction project.</p><p>There. The eyes. His brother&#39;s eyes were calm. Bobi&#39;s eyes were <em>watching</em> \u2014 watching his brother, watching the aunts, watching his mother&#39;s back as she washed dishes that would never be clean enough.</p><p>The difference was small. Maybe it wasn&#39;t even there. Maybe it was a trick of light, or angle, or the black spots in the mirror where the silver had decayed.</p><p>But the village had seen it. The village had named it. And once the village names a thing, the thing becomes true.</p><p><em>Kembar</em>. Twin.</p><p><em>Si jelek</em>. The ugly one.</p><p>The words were never spoken to his face. Not directly. But they were spoken in his presence, which was worse. They were spoken as if he were not there, as if ugliness conferred invisibility, as if the ugly twin were a thing to be discussed rather than a person to be addressed.</p><p>He was eight. Or nine. Old enough to understand debt. Old enough to understand that he had been born owing something. An apology. An explanation. A reason why the genes had produced <em>this</em> instead of <em>that</em>.</p><p>He looked at his brother in the mirror.</p>"
