        "title": "Chapter 2: The Digital Filter (9/30)",
        "content": "<p>Second: the features. They emerged from the pixel grid like something developing in chemical solution. Nose bridge. Cheekbones. Mouth.</p><p>Third: the details. And here Bobi leaned forward, his own face moving closer to the screen until the blue glow touched his skin.</p><p>The freckles.</p><p>They scattered across the bridge of her nose and the upper curves of her cheeks\u2014small, irregular, the kind that darkened in summer and faded in winter. Bobi counted seven on the left side of her nose, five on the right. They formed a pattern he would later recognize in the water stains on his ceiling, in the cracks in the bathroom tile, in the random distribution of things that pretended to be chaos but were actually a map.</p><p>Her skin had the quality of wet porcelain\u2014translucent, with a pink undertone that caught the lamp light and held it. Not the matte finish of Klaudia&#39;s makeup or the severe clarity of Julia&#39;s angles. Something softer. Something that looked like it would bruise if you pressed too hard.</p><p>Her eyes opened wider as her video stabilized. Pale blue-grey, the color of water in a shallow pool when light moves across the bottom. They looked at the screen\u2014at the grid, at the assembled rectangles\u2014and for a moment, Bobi felt them looking at <em>him specifically</em>, even though his camera was still off, even though his rectangle was still black.</p><p>&quot;Sorry, sorry,&quot; she said. &quot;My internet was being difficult.&quot;</p><p>Her voice moved through the laptop speakers like velvet dragged across something sharp. The Flemish accent rounded her vowels, made her consonants slightly musical. She pronounced &quot;difficult&quot; with the stress on the second syllable: diff-i-CULT.</p><p>&quot;No problem,&quot; Kyle said. &quot;We&#39;re just getting started.&quot;</p><p>&quot;Hi, everyone.&quot; She waved\u2014a small gesture, hand moving near her face. &quot;I&#39;m Eline. I set up the group, so I&#39;m glad you all could make it.&quot;</p>"
