        "content": "<p>He traced her jawline on the cold glass\u2014starting below her left ear, following the curve down to her chin, up the other side. The glass was smooth, unyielding. His fingertip left a small smear of oil.</p><p>For a moment\u2014brief, no longer than the space between heartbeats\u2014he imagined the glass as something else. Sharper. Thinner. The kind of edge that would part skin if you pressed it at the correct angle.</p><p>The screen as a surgical instrument.</p><p>The thought arrived and departed without ceremony. It left no residue except a faint warmth in his chest, like the first sip of <em>Cap Tikus</em> before the burn.</p><p>&quot;So,&quot; Eline said, addressing the group, &quot;I thought we could do a casual introduction round. Just who you are, where you&#39;re from, what you&#39;re hoping to get out of the group. Nothing formal.&quot;</p><p>The grid rearranged slightly as people shifted in their chairs. Bobi&#39;s rectangle remained black\u2014a void among the lit faces.</p><p>Kyle went first, describing his work in tech, his interest in cultural exchange, his time spent between Shenzhen and Vancouver. His face was symmetrical even when he spoke\u2014jaw moving without disturbing the architectural precision of his features.</p><p>Julia followed, her introduction clipped: &quot;Warsaw. HR work. Looking to practice English with people who aren&#39;t trying to sell me something.&quot;</p><p>Klaudia: &quot;Also Warsaw. Social media stuff. I just think it&#39;s cool to meet people from everywhere, you know?&quot;</p><p>Mina&#39;s black rectangle: &quot;Djibouti. Nursing. My English needs work.&quot;</p>"
