        "content": "<p>&quot;Great! See you all next week,&quot; Eline said. She waved at her camera\u2014the kind of wave that showed her palm and looked childlike and unselfconscious in a way that people from careful cultures could never quite replicate.</p><p>Her camera turned off. The warm rectangle collapsed to black. Her name tag remained.</p><p>Kyle disconnected next. Then Julia and Klaudia together, their cameras dying simultaneously\u2014coordinated even in departure. Mina&#39;s rectangle had already been dark; now her name tag vanished as well.</p><p>Bobi sat alone with six empty rectangles arranged in a grid. The ghost of the call. The architecture of connection with no one left inside it.</p><p>He closed the chat window. The grid disappeared. His desktop showed\u2014the unnamed folder three directories deep, the file names that were just numbers, the thumbnails too small to reveal their contents without opening.</p><p>He touched his face. His fingers found his cheek, his jaw, his nose. Everything felt as it always felt\u2014warm, oily, the topography he&#39;d lived inside for thirty-one years. His fingertips discovered nothing wrong. No blood. No wound. Just skin doing what skin did, holding everything inside where it belonged.</p><p>In the window&#39;s reflection, the Brother sat unchanged in his corner. The angle of the reflected image made it look like the Brother was watching the empty chair where Bobi had been rather than Bobi himself.</p><p>The blood on Bobi&#39;s cheek had dried. The small dot had darkened, turned the colour of old rust, become part of the landscape of his face. Invisible to him. Visible to anyone who looked carefully at the right angle in the right light.</p><p>But no one was looking anymore.</p><p>The call was over. The grid was empty. The fluorescent tube buzzed its constant note. Outside, the rain that had been building all evening finally arrived, drumming against the tin roof with the sound of ten thousand small decisions happening at once.</p>"
