        "title": "Chapter 3: The \"Identical\" Incision (21/22)",
        "content": "<p>Bobi did not turn on the overhead light. He sat in the blue glow from his screen and the narrow dawn beam that would arrive in hours, and he thought about the word <em>beautiful</em> in Eline&#39;s voice, in Eline&#39;s mouth, directed at him\u2014at him and the Brother both, <em>identical</em> and therefore equally deserving of the word that he had never once in thirty-one years believed applied to the face he carried.</p><p>The trembling in his hand had stopped.</p><p>Everything was very still.</p><p>Bobi sat motionless, the blue glow from his laptop casting eerie shadows on his face. The fluorescent tube above flickered intermittently, its buzz a steady drone that filled the silence left by the ended call. The room was a tableau of stillness, a moment suspended between decision and action.</p><p>He turned his gaze to the cracked mirror on the wall. His reflection stared back, a face he had long despised, now split into two misaligned halves by the diagonal fissure. Beside it, the laptop screen displayed the Brother&#39;s silhouette, a darker presence in the corner of the room, a promise of what could be. Two versions of his face, two realities coexisting in the dim light.</p><p>The decision came quietly, methodically, like scheduling a mundane task. He would correct the nose first. The nose was the worst offender, the <em>hidung kampung</em> that had always marked him as lesser, as the ugly twin. It had to go. He felt a strange calm, a detachment from the gravity of what he was about to do. It was simply a task, a step in a process that had been inevitable from the moment Eline uttered the word &quot;identical.&quot;</p><p>He stood and walked to the small shelf by the door, where a few packets of instant noodles and a single plate sat. Among them was a kitchen knife, its blade dulled by years of use. He picked it up, testing its edge against his thumb. A thin red line appeared, a promise of sharpness. He nodded, satisfied.</p><p>Next, he retrieved the half-empty bottle of <em>Cap Tikus</em> moonshine from under the bed. The clear liquid sloshed inside, its astringent smell filling the air as he uncapped it. He set it on the desk beside the laptop, the harsh scent mingling with the faint smell of Betadine and old clove cigarettes that lingered in the room.</p><p>The fishing line was already in the room, coiled neatly on the desk. He had bought it weeks ago, telling himself it was for a repair he never intended to make. Now, he admitted its true purpose. He unspooled a length, feeling its wiry strength between his fingers.</p><p>Finally, he took the sewing needle from his pocket, the same one he had used in the bathroom. It was small, silver, its eye threaded with nothing but potential. He laid it on the towel beside the other tools, arranging them with the precision of a surgeon preparing for an operation.</p>"
