        "chapter": 4,
        "isChapterStart": true,
        "title": "Chapter 4: Scalpel and Stone (1/11)",
        "content": "<p>The first glass burned like fire. Bobi tipped it back, the clear liquid searing a path down his throat, igniting his stomach. He gasped, eyes watering, but didn\u2019t stop. The second went down easier, the heat spreading through his chest, radiating outward like a slow explosion. His fingers tingled. His scalp pulsed. By the third, the burn was distant, a memory of pain rather than pain itself. The moonshine settled in his veins, a dull, warm weight, the kind of numbness that felt like mercy.</p><p>&quot;Village anesthesia,&quot; he murmured, setting the empty bottle aside. The words slurred slightly, his tongue thick. Not drunk\u2014never drunk. Just <em>prepared</em>. The peasant\u2019s mercy, his mother used to call it when the toothaches came. He wiped his mouth with the back of his hand, the scent of <em>Cap Tikus</em> sharp and chemical, cutting through the Betadine\u2019s sweet, brown smell already clinging to his skin.</p><p>The laptop screen glowed, the paused tutorial waiting. Bobi leaned in, tracing the surgeon\u2019s movements with his fingertip. The cross-section diagram showed the nose in layers\u2014skin, fat, cartilage, bone. He whispered the terms to himself, his accent twisting the words: <em>&quot;the under-skin... the nose bridge bone...&quot;</em> His finger followed the dotted lines where the incisions would go, where the cartilage would be reshaped. The surgeon\u2019s hands were steady, gloved, professional. Bobi\u2019s were bare, calloused, trembling only slightly. He flexed them, watching the tendons shift beneath his skin. Tools were tools. A knife was a knife.</p><p>He adjusted the mirror first, angling it so his nose was caught in profile, the bridge thrown into sharp relief by the fluorescent light. The crack in the glass split his face unevenly, one half wider than the other, as if the mirror itself knew which side was the draft and which was the final version. He ignored the distortion. The goal wasn\u2019t accuracy\u2014it was <em>improvement</em>.</p><p>Then the laptop. He dragged Eline\u2019s screenshot beside the mirror, her face glowing golden in the blue light. Her nose was straight, the bridge narrow, the tip refined. He measured the distance with his thumb and forefinger, holding them up to his own reflection. Too wide. Too flat. The <em>hidung kampung</em>, the village nose, his aunt\u2019s voice hissed in his memory. He pressed his fingers harder against his skin, as if he could already feel the knife\u2019s edge there.</p><p>The room smelled like a hospital and a <em>warung</em> after last call. The <em>Cap Tikus</em> fumes mixed with the Betadine\u2019s antiseptic bite, the old <em>kretek</em> smoke embedded in the walls, the copper tang of the blood from his thumb where he\u2019d tested the knife. Outside, the rain picked up, drumming against the tin roof in uneven bursts, like a thousand fingers tapping impatiently. The fluorescent tube buzzed overhead, a steady, maddening hum, the sound of the room holding its breath.</p><p>He picked up the knife.</p><p>The metal was cool against his skin, the blade resting just above the bridge of his nose. He didn\u2019t press yet. He breathed in through his nose, out through his mouth, the way his mother had taught him before the <em>pengucapan syukur</em> ceremonies, when the air in the church got too thick with incense and whispers. His reflection wavered in the cracked glass, the knife\u2019s edge a thin, silver promise.</p><p>A folk song rose in his throat before he realized he was humming. The melody was old, older than the village, older than the debt. His mother\u2019s voice, her fingers combing through his hair\u2014<em>his</em> hair, before it had fallen out\u2014before the aunts\u2019 hands had learned to pat instead of squeeze, before the Brother had become the standard and he the apology. The notes filled the room, rich and low, the kind of sound that belonged in a house with a proper floor and walls that didn\u2019t sweat. He let it vibrate in his chest, steadying himself.</p><p>The Brother sat in his corner, silent. Watching. Always watching. Bobi didn\u2019t turn to look. He didn\u2019t need to. The Brother was there in the reflection, too, just beyond the edge of the mirror\u2019s frame, a darker shape in the darkness. A promise.</p>"
