        "title": "Chapter 4: Scalpel and Stone (3/11)",
        "content": "<p>The knife pressed harder.</p><p>The skin resisted\u2014just for a heartbeat, a final stubborn protest\u2014then parted. The blade slid in with a sound like tearing silk, but wetter, deeper. <em>Shrit-shrit.</em> The noise filled the room, sharp and intimate, the kind of sound that belonged in an operating theater, not a rented room with peeling walls and a buzzing light. Bobi exhaled through his nose, the breath hitching as the metal met cartilage. The resistance was different here, denser, like cutting through gristle. He adjusted his grip, angling the knife to follow the dotted lines he\u2019d memorized from the tutorial. His free hand braced against his cheek, fingers splayed, holding the skin taut.</p><p>Blood welled immediately, warm and copper-scented, trickling down his philtrum to his lip. He tasted it before he could wipe it away\u2014metallic, thick, like the <em>coto</em> broth his mother used to make, before the church ladies told her it was too Muslim, too village, too much. He swallowed. The taste grounded him.</p><p>The knife moved again. <em>Shrit-shrit.</em> This time deeper, scraping against the cartilage. The sound changed pitch, higher, almost musical. He hummed along with it, a counter-melody to the folk song still stuck in his throat. The blade caught on something\u2014fibrous, unyielding. He bore down. The cartilage gave with a wet <em>snick</em>, the noise too loud in the small room. His vision blurred for a second, the mirror\u2019s reflection swimming, but he blinked it clear. The Brother didn\u2019t flinch in the corner. Of course he didn\u2019t. He was waiting.</p><p>Bobi set the knife down on the towel, handle-first, the blade glistening. His fingers probed the incision. The skin was already swelling, the edges puffy and warm. He pressed harder, exploring the new landscape beneath. The cartilage felt wrong now\u2014uneven, jagged where he\u2019d cut. The tutorial surgeon had used a rasp, a delicate tool for refining. Bobi had a kitchen knife and a steady hand. He\u2019d make do.</p><p>He picked the knife back up.</p><p>The next cut went deeper, following the bridge downward. The <em>shrit-shrit</em> came faster now, a rhythm, the knife working like a chisel against stone. Blood ran freely, dripping onto the towel, the desk, the keyboard. A drop landed on Eline\u2019s face in the screenshot, sliding down her cheek like a tear. He didn\u2019t wipe it. The pixel would forgive him. It always did.</p><p>His fingers slipped on the knife handle. He tightened his grip, knuckles white. The cartilage wasn\u2019t coming free cleanly\u2014it was attached, stubborn, part of him in a way the tutorial hadn\u2019t prepared him for. He sawed gently, the blade catching, releasing, catching again. The sound changed, became wetter, messier. He didn\u2019t mind. Progress wasn\u2019t clean. He knew that from the village, from the way his mother\u2019s hands had calloused over years of scrubbing other people\u2019s laundry, from the way the Brother had always been loved more despite being no different. No, less different now. The knife was making them the same.</p><p>A chunk of cartilage came loose. He pinched it between his fingers, holding it up to the light. Yellow-white, slick with blood, the texture of overcooked chicken fat. He set it aside on the towel. Waste material. The building\u2019s old wiring, being stripped out.</p><p>He went back in.</p>"
