        "title": "Chapter 4: Scalpel and Stone (4/11)",
        "content": "<p>The knife scraped again, deeper this time, reshaping the bridge. He was carving it narrower, sharper, like the surgeon in the video, like the nose he\u2019d seen on Kyle\u2019s face during the calls, like the one in Eline\u2019s screenshot, smooth and unbroken. His own nose was too wide, too flat\u2014the <em>hidung kampung</em>, the village nose, the one the aunts had pinched between their fingers when they thought he wasn\u2019t looking. <em>Like this, sayang,</em> one had said once, pressing her thumbs to the sides of his nose, as if she could mold it like clay. <em>Pretty boys have narrow noses.</em> He\u2019d laughed his village laugh and run outside, where the Brother was already waiting, already perfect.</p><p>The memory steadied his hand.</p><p>He cut again. The knife slipped this time, the tip skidding off the cartilage and into the soft tissue beside it. Pain flared, bright and hot, but he didn\u2019t pull back. Pain was information. It told him where the edges were. He adjusted, recutting the line, following the blood\u2019s path like a roadmap. The subcutaneous fat emerged\u2014pale yellow, glistening, the texture of warm tallow. He wiped it on the towel without looking. His focus was on the structure beneath, the bones and cartilage, the things that held the face up. The fat was just insulation. It could be removed.</p><p>The room smelled like a butcher\u2019s stall now, copper and salt and something older, something like the damp in the church walls after the monsoon. The fluorescent light buzzed steadily, the rain drumming against the tin roof in uneven bursts. His reflection in the mirror was smeared with blood, the crack in the glass splitting his face into two unequal halves. One side was swolen, the nose already misshapen, the skin puffy and red. The other side was still him\u2014still <em>jelek</em>, still owing. He ignored it. The mirror was a liar. The webcam was kinder.</p><p>He reached for Eline\u2019s screenshot, his bloody fingers leaving streaks on the screen. Her face was still there beneath the red, still golden, still perfect. He pressed his thumb to her nose bridge, then to his own, measuring. Closer. Not there yet, but closer.</p><p>\u201cThis is for you,\u201d he murmured.</p><p>The words felt right in his mouth, true in a way nothing had been true since the village. He wasn\u2019t cutting. He was <em>building</em>. The burn in his nose wasn\u2019t pain\u2014it was the old structure coming down, the condemned building making way for the new. He could feel it in his bones, the way the cartilage gave under the knife, the way the skin parted like it had been waiting. The Brother knew. The Brother had always known.</p><p>He went back to work.</p><p>The knife moved with more confidence now, the <em>shrit-shrit</em> a steady rhythm, the sound of progress. He scraped and carved, reshaping the bridge, narrowing the tip. Blood ran down his face, dripping onto the desk, the towel, the floor. His hands were slick with it, his fingers leaving red prints on everything they touched\u2014the keyboard, the mouse, the edge of the mirror. He didn\u2019t stop to clean them. There would be time for that later. Now was for the work.</p><p>The subcutaneous fat emerged again, pale and glistening. He wiped it aside, focusing on the structure beneath. The cartilage was coming free in uneven chunks, the nose\u2019s shape changing under his hands. He could feel it\u2014could <em>see</em> it, even through the blood and swelling. The bridge was narrower now, sharper. The tip was more refined. He was getting there. He was getting <em>closer</em>.</p>"
