        "content": "<p><em>Good.</em></p><p><em>Closer.</em></p><p><em>Almost there.</em></p><p>The needle slid through the fishing line\u2019s eye with a whisper, the transparent thread catching the laptop\u2019s blue glow like a strand of spider silk. Bobi\u2019s fingers were steady now, the <em>Cap Tikus</em> humming in his veins, the adrenaline sharpening his focus. He held the needle up to the light, watching the line unspool slightly, a thin, almost invisible thread that would hold his new face together. The spool sat beside the keyboard, the plastic edge smeared with blood where his fingers had brushed against it.</p><p>He turned back to the mirror.</p><p>His reflection was a mess\u2014blood streaked down his cheeks, his nose swollen and raw, the skin around it puffy and red. But beneath the blood, he could see the change. The bridge was narrower. The tip was sharper. It wasn\u2019t perfect yet, but it was <em>better</em>. The old structure was coming down, and the new one was rising in its place. He could feel it in his bones.</p><p>He pressed the needle to the skin beside his nostril.</p><p>The first puncture was always the hardest.</p><p>He pushed.</p><p>The skin resisted for a second\u2014then gave with a sound like a wet finger pulling free from a tight grip. <em>Pop.</em> The needle slid through, the fishing line following, the thread biting into the flesh. He pulled it taut, the skin puckering around the entry point, fresh blood welling up around the puncture. He didn\u2019t flinch. This was progress. This was <em>building</em>.</p>"
