        "title": "Chapter 4: Scalpel and Stone (7/11)",
        "content": "<p>He moved to the next stitch.</p><p>The needle went in again\u2014<em>pop</em>\u2014and out the other side, the fishing line drawing the edges of the wound together. The skin resisted at first, the swelling making it difficult to align, but he pulled harder, the flesh giving way with a wet, yielding sound. The stitches marched across his skin like the legs of a black centipede, each puncture a step closer to completion. The fishing line gleamed in the fluorescent light, the transparent thread catching the blue glow of the laptop screen, the stitches pulling his new nose into place.</p><p>He worked methodically, his breath coming in short, controlled bursts through his mouth. His nose was packed with toilet paper, the blood-soaked wad pressing against the raw wound, the air passing through the gaps in the packing with a wet, rattling sound. He could taste the <em>Cap Tikus</em> at the back of his throat, the sharp burn of the moonshine mixing with the copper tang of blood. He didn\u2019t mind. It was part of the process. The body was adjusting. The structure was settling.</p><p>The stitches were uneven in places, the fishing line pulling too tight in some spots, too loose in others. But it didn\u2019t matter. This was just the first layer. There would be more. There would always be more until it was perfect. Until it was <em>identical</em>.</p><p>He tied off the last stitch, the knot pulling tight against his skin. The fishing line dug into the flesh, the pressure a dull, throbbing ache. He didn\u2019t mind that either. Pain was information. It told him where the edges were. It told him what still needed to be fixed.</p><p>He set the needle down on the towel, the metal dark with blood. The spool of fishing line was nearly empty, the transparent thread coiled loosely around the plastic. He\u2019d need more soon. But for now, it was enough.</p><p>He turned to the Brother.</p><p>The Brother sat in the corner, silent as always, the laptop\u2019s glow casting long shadows across his face. Bobi couldn\u2019t see his features clearly\u2014not in the dim light, not with his vision blurred from the blood and the moonshine\u2014but he didn\u2019t need to. He knew what the Brother would say.</p><p>\u201cWe are closer now,\u201d Bobi murmured.</p><p>The Brother didn\u2019t respond.</p>"
