        "title": "Chapter 4: Scalpel and Stone (8/11)",
        "content": "<p>He never did.</p><p>Bobi took the silence as approval.</p><p>He flexed his fingers, the tips stiff from the blood and the tension. The room smelled like copper and antiseptic, the scent of the <em>Cap Tikus</em> lingering beneath it, sharp and chemical. The fluorescent light buzzed steadily overhead, the rain still drumming against the tin roof in uneven bursts. The towel on the desk was dark with blood, the keyboard smeared with red where his fingers had slipped. The mirror was streaked, his reflection split by the crack in the glass\u2014one side swollen and stitched, the other still <em>jelek</em>, still owing.</p><p>He didn\u2019t look at that side.</p><p>He didn\u2019t need to.</p><p>He knew what it would say.</p><p>He reached for the toilet paper again, pressing a fresh wad against his nostril. The blood had slowed, the wound finally clotting, the fishing line stitches holding the flesh together in uneven rows. He could feel the pull of them with every breath, the tension in his skin, the way the new shape settled against the old. It wasn\u2019t perfect. Not yet. But it was closer.</p><p>He turned back to the desk.</p><p>The knife lay beside the needle, the blade dark with blood, the edge nicked from hitting bone. The spool of fishing line was nearly empty, the transparent thread coiled loosely around the plastic. The laptop screen still glowed, Eline\u2019s paused screenshot beside it, her golden face untouched by the blood, the chaos, the <em>building</em>. She was still there. She was still perfect.</p><p>He reached out, his fingers leaving a red print on the screen as he traced the line of her nose.</p>"
