        "title": "Chapter 4: Scalpel and Stone (10/11)",
        "content": "<p>The morning light crept through the broken slats of the louvered window, a thin surgical blade of gold cutting across the room. It found Bobi\u2019s face first\u2014swollen, stitched, the nose a purple-black mass twice its usual size. The toilet paper plugging his nostril had dried overnight, stiff with blood, the edges curling like dead leaves. He didn\u2019t move at first. His neck ached from sleeping hunched over the desk, his fingers stiff where blood had crusted between them. The room smelled like old copper and Betadine, the antiseptic\u2019s sweet, brown scent clinging to everything\u2014the towel, the keyboard, the cracks in the mirror.</p><p>He blinked. The light shifted. The pain in his face was a dull, throbbing pulse, the fishing line stitches pulling with every breath. He didn\u2019t mind. Pain was just the body talking. And the body was saying: <em>progress</em>.</p><p>He stood slowly, the chair scraping against the linoleum. The mirror hung crooked on the wall, the crack splitting his reflection into two uneven halves. He leaned in. The left side of his face\u2014the side the crack favoured\u2014showed the new nose, swollen but already sharper, the bridge narrower beneath the bruising. The right side was still <em>jelek</em>, still owing, but he ignored it. He focused on the left. The scaffolding was up. The renovation had begun.</p><p>\u201cThe bridge has been rebuilt,\u201d he murmured. His voice sounded thick, the words slurring slightly around the swelling. \u201cStronger. Truer.\u201d The bruising was just the dust of construction, the mess that came before the reveal. He pressed his fingertips to the stitches, tracing the black centipede of fishing line marching across his skin. The flesh puckered where the thread pulled too tight, the knots digging into the swollen tissue. It wasn\u2019t perfect. Not yet. But it was closer.</p><p>He turned to the desk. The laptop was still open, the screen dark. He tapped the space bar. The display flickered to life, the blue glow washing over his hands, the dried blood on his fingers turning black under the light. Eline\u2019s screenshot waited beside the webcam preview. He clicked the preview icon. The low resolution softened everything\u2014the swelling became strong bone structure, the bruising melted into shadow, the stitches blurred into dark lines that could have been anything. Contour. Definition. The pixel was kind. The pixel understood.</p><p>He angled the camera, tilting his head to catch the light just right. The left side of his face\u2014the good side\u2014filled the frame. He took a selfie. The shutter sound was a quiet <em>click</em>, the image capturing the new nose, the fishing line stitches, the purple-black bruising that would, in time, fade to nothing. He placed the photo beside Eline\u2019s screenshot. Side by side. Before and after.</p><p>The gap had narrowed.</p><p>Not by much. Millimeters, maybe. But millimeters were the difference between <em>jelek</em> and <em>kembar</em>. Between owing and owed. Between the village and the screen.</p><p>He zoomed in. Eline\u2019s nose was still perfect\u2014slim, symmetrical, the bridge a clean line from brow to tip. His was wider, the swelling distorting the shape, the stitches pulling the flesh into uneven peaks. But the foundation was there. The bones were stronger now. The structure was sound.</p><p>He saved the photo. He didn\u2019t name the file. He didn\u2019t need to.</p>"
