        "content": "<p>The fluorescent tube flickered, casting a sickly yellow glow over the room. Bobi stood, his body stiff from the night spent on the thin mattress, the stitches in his nose pulling with every movement. He didn\u2019t mind the discomfort. It was proof. Evidence of progress.</p><p>He turned toward the corner.</p><p>The Brother sat in the plastic chair, his posture perfect, his hands resting on his knees. The morning light slanted through the louvered window, touching his shoulder, turning the dark strands of his hair into something liquid, something alive. Bobi stepped closer. The floor creaked under his weight, the sound swallowed by the hum of the fluorescent tube, the distant murmur of the city outside.</p><p>He reached out.</p><p>The Brother\u2019s hair was the first thing he touched. It was long, thick, black\u2014impossible silk between his fingers. He ran his hand through it, feeling the strands slide against his palm, cool and smooth. The texture was perfect. The way it caught the light, the way it moved\u2014it was everything his own scalp wasn\u2019t. His scalp was a naked, pulsing vulnerability, the skin hot and damp, the pores always weeping in the humidity. The Brother\u2019s hair was dry. Still. It didn\u2019t sweat. It didn\u2019t flush. It didn\u2019t betray.</p><p>Bobi leaned in closer.</p><p>The Brother\u2019s face was identical to his own\u2014but corrected. The jawline was sharper, the angle more defined, the kind of bone structure that made aunts lean in to kiss first. The skin was smooth, poreless, the kind of surface that didn\u2019t trap heat or shine with oil. The eyes were open. Always open. They didn\u2019t blink. They didn\u2019t shift. They didn\u2019t judge. They just <em>were</em>\u2014dark, still, the pupils slightly too large, like windows into a room with no one inside.</p><p>Bobi\u2019s fingers brushed the Brother\u2019s cheek.</p><p>The skin was smooth. Cold. Not the cold of living flesh, but the cold of something that had never been warm. There was a tackiness to it, like drying latex, the surface yielding slightly under his touch but never quite soft. He pressed harder. The flesh\u2014if it was flesh\u2014gave just enough to suggest depth, but there was no warmth beneath it. No pulse. No breath. Just the faintest resistance, like pressing against a wall that had been painted to look like skin.</p><p>He didn\u2019t question it.</p>"
