        "title": "Chapter 5: The Silk Harvest (13/16)",
        "content": "<p>The reflection stared back. His scalp\u2014no, <em>their</em> scalp\u2014was covered now. Dark strands clung to the skin, uneven but <em>there</em>, a crown of what should have always been his. The Brother\u2019s hair. His hair. The hair the aunts had touched first, the hair the village had admired, the hair that had been kissed while his own bald skin was patted like an afterthought. Now it was his. Now it was where it belonged.</p><p>He tilted his head slightly, studying the effect. The crack in the mirror split the image, but even through the distortion, the improvement was undeniable. The strands were dark, thick in places, sparse in others, but that didn\u2019t matter. The architecture was sound. The foundation was laid. He reached up, his fingers brushing against the new hair, feeling the texture\u2014coarse in some patches, smooth in others, the adhesive beneath slightly tacky where it hadn\u2019t fully dried. It was perfect. It was <em>his</em>.</p><p>Behind him, the Brother sat motionless in the corner, the chair creaking slightly under the weight of what remained. The Brother\u2019s own scalp was uneven now, patches of exposed material showing through where the hair had been taken. But the Brother didn\u2019t need it. The Brother had given it freely. The Brother understood.</p><p>Bobi turned his head again, examining the profile. The nose was still swollen from the previous surgery, the sutures pulling slightly, the skin purpled with bruising. But the hair\u2014<em>his</em> hair\u2014drew the eye upward, balanced the proportions, corrected the flaws. He traced the line of his jaw in the reflection, imagining how it would look once the next phase was complete. The jaw was weak still, soft where the Brother\u2019s was sharp. But that would change. That would be fixed. For now, this was enough. This was progress.</p><p>He stepped back, his bare feet pressing against the cracked linoleum. The room smelled of Betadine and old blood, of <em>Cap Tikus</em> and the sharp chemical tang of the adhesive. The air was thick, humid, the kind of heat that made everything feel alive, even the walls. Even the mirror.</p><p>He turned to the laptop.</p><p>The screen glowed blue in the dim room, the webcam preview already open. He adjusted the angle slightly, tilting the laptop until his face filled the small rectangle. The resolution was low\u2014480p, the way he liked it. The way that forgave.</p><p>In the preview, the changes were subtle but undeniable. The dark mass on his scalp could be hair. The blood was invisible, the swelling just shadow, the uneven strands softened by the pixels. He tilted his head again, watching how the light caught the strands, how they moved slightly as he shifted. It was convincing. It was <em>real</em>.</p><p>A laugh bubbled up in his chest.</p><p>It started as the village laugh\u2014the wide, toothy grin, the cheeks pushed high, the performance of joy. But this time, something was different. The laugh didn\u2019t feel hollow. It didn\u2019t feel like a mask. His cheeks ached slightly from the sutures, the skin pulling, but he didn\u2019t care. He laughed again, louder this time, the sound filling the small room, bouncing off the water-stained walls, mixing with the rain on the tin roof, the fluorescent buzz, the Brother\u2019s silence.</p>"
