        "content": "<p>The digital <em>click</em> of Kyle placing his first settlement on the Colonist board echoed through the call, sharp and decisive. Bobi watched the screen, the hexagonal grid of the game board filling his vision\u2014green for wood, yellow for grain, red for brick, grey for ore, white for sheep. To the others, it was just a game. To Bobi, it was a map.</p><p>A map of a face.</p><p>Each hex was a pore. Each intersection a potential incision point. Each road a suture line, a thread pulling skin taut over bone. The settlements\u2014those little house icons\u2014were flags planted in conquered territory. Kyle\u2019s settlements, specifically. Kyle\u2019s flags.</p><p>Bobi\u2019s camera was on, the resolution low, the lighting dim. His face filled the small rectangle on the grid, the dark mass of his transplanted hair visible, the sutures on his nose less pronounced now, healing badly but healing. The group had noticed the changes. He could tell. The way Julia\u2019s eyes flicked to his rectangle a little too often. The way Klaudia\u2019s reactions had grown slightly delayed, her emojis arriving a beat late, as if she were distracted by something she couldn\u2019t quite place. The way Eline\u2019s voice had grown softer when she spoke to him, as if she were afraid of startling him.</p><p>But no one had said anything. Not yet.</p><p>The pixel was still his accomplice.</p><p>Kyle\u2019s face dominated the screen, not just because of the game, but because of the way he occupied space. His lighting was perfect\u2014matte, even, expensive. His features were symmetrical, his jaw sharp enough to cut glass, his skin smooth as polished stone. Bobi\u2019s fingers twitched toward his own jawline, tracing the softness there, the give of flesh where there should have been definition. Weak. Feminine. <em>Village.</em></p><p>Kyle placed another settlement. Another <em>click.</em> Another flag.</p><p>\u201cWood and brick,\u201d Kyle said, his voice measured, confident. \u201cGood start.\u201d</p><p>Bobi barely heard him. He was watching Kyle\u2019s jawline on the screen, the way it caught the light, the way it held its shape no matter how he moved. A foundation. A structure. Something built to last.</p>"
