        "title": "Chapter 6: The Colonist's Architecture (2/19)",
        "content": "<p>His own jaw ached faintly beneath his fingers, the plastic shards from his earlier attempts still shifting beneath the skin, the sutures from his nose surgery pulling slightly as he clenched his teeth. He could feel the difference\u2014the softness, the lack of definition, the way his flesh yielded where Kyle\u2019s resisted.</p><p><em>I\u2019m taking this territory,</em> Kyle had said earlier, when he\u2019d claimed the first settlement spot. <em>Nothing personal.</em></p><p>Bobi had heard it then, too. Not about the game. About everything.</p><p>Eline laughed at something Klaudia said, the sound warm, golden, the kind of laugh that made you want to lean toward it, to be the reason for it. Bobi\u2019s fingers pressed harder against his jaw, the bone beneath giving slightly, too pliable, too malleable. Not like Kyle\u2019s. Not like the Brother\u2019s.</p><p>He could fix that.</p><p>The thought arrived fully formed, a revelation. The jaw was the next target. The jaw was the next territory to claim.</p><p>His turn came. He rolled the dice\u2014virtually, on-screen\u2014a seven. Resources distributed. He had grain. Sheep. Nothing useful. Nothing that would let him build. Nothing that would let him <em>conquer.</em></p><p>He placed a road anyway, a thin line stretching across the board, a suture pulling skin taut. It didn\u2019t matter where. It didn\u2019t matter how. He just needed to mark the space. To claim it. To show that he was there.</p><p>Klaudia sent a heart emoji into the chat. Julia was silent, her camera rectangle a study in stillness, her eyes narrowed slightly, her head tilted just enough to suggest she was watching something other than the game. Bobi didn\u2019t look at her. He didn\u2019t need to. He could feel the weight of her gaze, the way it lingered on his rectangle a second too long, the way it flicked to Kyle\u2019s face, comparing, measuring, finding him lacking.</p><p>He muted his mic.</p>"
