        "title": "Chapter 6: The Colonist's Architecture (5/19)",
        "content": "<p>\u201cI\u2019m taking this territory,\u201d he said. \u201cNothing personal.\u201d</p><p>Bobi didn\u2019t look up.</p><p>He already knew.</p><p>The game board glowed on Bobi\u2019s screen, hexagonal tiles bathed in the laptop\u2019s blue light, while Kyle\u2019s voice cut through the group\u2019s chatter like a scalpel. <em>&quot;Ore on a six. Good spot.&quot;</em> His cursor hovered, then clicked\u2014a settlement placed, another piece of the map claimed. The digital <em>thunk</em> of the house dropping onto the hex echoed in Bobi\u2019s earbuds, sharp and final.</p><p>Bobi\u2019s rectangle on the grid was the darkest, his face half-lost in shadow, the low resolution blurring the edges of his jawline where the plastic shards from his last attempt still shifted beneath the skin. His fingers twitched against his desk, brushing the edge of the broken phone case he\u2019d salvaged from the <em>warung</em> two streets over. The plastic was hard, unyielding\u2014nothing like the softness of his own flesh. He pressed a jagged piece against his jaw, feeling the angle, the way it resisted the give of his skin. <em>This could work.</em></p><p>On-screen, Eline rolled the dice\u2014a five. <em>&quot;Grain and wood. Not bad!&quot;</em> Her rectangle was all warm light and soft focus, her freckles like constellations Bobi had memorized. He watched her lips move, the way they curved around words, the way her jaw held its shape when she laughed. A structure. A foundation. Something built to last.</p><p>His other hand\u2014hidden below the camera\u2019s frame\u2014dug into the pocket of his shorts. The river stones were there, smooth and cold, collected during his last supply run when he\u2019d walked too far from the <em>kos-kosan</em>, following the sound of water until he found the shallow creek where the rocks lay half-buried in the mud. He\u2019d chosen the flattest ones, the ones that fit against his palm like they belonged there. Like they belonged <em>in</em> there.</p><p>Kyle\u2019s voice again: <em>&quot;Trade? Julia, I\u2019ll give you two sheep for that ore.&quot;</em> The cursor dragged a road across the board, another line drawn, another claim staked.</p><p>Bobi pressed the plastic shard harder against his jaw. The edge bit into his skin, not enough to break it, but enough to feel the resistance, the way his flesh pushed back before giving way. <em>Ore.</em> That\u2019s what Kyle had called it. The hard stuff. The stuff you built with. The stuff you <em>needed</em> if you wanted to win.</p><p>His jaw ached where the plastic dug in. He adjusted the angle, imagining the shard beneath his skin, the way it would press against the bone, the way it would force his flesh into something sharper, something stronger. Something like Kyle\u2019s. Something like the Brother\u2019s.</p>"
