        "chapter": 6,
        "isChapterStart": false,
        "title": "Chapter 6: The Colonist's Architecture (6/19)",
        "content": "<p>The Brother sat in his corner, silent as always, his jawline a perfect arc in the dim light. Bobi didn\u2019t look at him. He didn\u2019t need to. He could feel the weight of that perfection, the way it pulled at him, the way it promised something better than what he had.</p><p>On-screen, the game continued. Klaudia sent another emoji\u2014a laughing face, something bright and empty. Julia\u2019s rectangle was still, her eyes flicking between the board and Bobi\u2019s dark square, her head tilted just slightly, like she was listening to something no one else could hear. Bobi ignored her. He ignored all of them, except for Kyle, except for the way his cursor moved, the way his settlements spread across the board like flags planted in conquered land.</p><p>Bobi\u2019s fingers tightened around the plastic shard. The edge pressed deeper, the skin around it turning white, then red. A bead of blood welled where the plastic bit in, but he didn\u2019t wipe it away. He let it sit there, a dark smear on his jawline, a mark of where the territory would be claimed.</p><p><em>&quot;I\u2019ll take this spot,&quot;</em> Kyle said, his cursor hovering over another hex. <em>&quot;Good ore numbers.&quot;</em></p><p>Bobi\u2019s breath hitched. His other hand\u2014the one not holding the plastic\u2014moved to his desk, brushing against the fishing line, the needle, the tube of adhesive. The tools were there, waiting. The game was almost over. Kyle was almost done winning.</p><p>And then Bobi would start.</p><p>He opened another tab on his browser, minimizing the game just enough to pull up the YouTube tutorial he\u2019d bookmarked days ago. The thumbnail showed a surgeon\u2019s gloved hands, a scalpel poised above a patient\u2019s jawline, the skin already marked with ink. Bobi had watched it before. He\u2019d watched it <em>many</em> times. But he needed to see it again. Needed to remind himself of the steps, the angles, the way the flesh parted when you knew what you were doing.</p><p>The video played on mute, the surgeon\u2019s hands moving with clinical precision, the skin peeling back to reveal the bone beneath. Bobi\u2019s fingers mimicked the movements, pressing the plastic shard against his jaw, imagining the cut, the way the flesh would resist before giving way, the way the shard would slide beneath the skin, the way it would <em>stay</em>.</p><p><em>&quot;Bobi?&quot;</em></p><p>Eline\u2019s voice. Warm. Concerned. He froze, his hand still pressed against his jaw, the plastic digging in. His rectangle was still dark, his face half-hidden, but she was looking at him. He could feel it.</p>"
