        "title": "Chapter 6: The Colonist's Architecture (7/19)",
        "content": "<p>&quot;Connection bad,&quot; he said, forcing the village laugh, the one that showed all his teeth and meant nothing. &quot;Sorry.&quot;</p><p>She smiled. <em>&quot;No worries. You okay?&quot;</em></p><p>His fingers twitched against the plastic. <em>&quot;Yes,&quot;</em> he said. <em>&quot;Is okay.&quot;</em></p><p>On-screen, Kyle placed another settlement. Another claim. Another piece of the board taken.</p><p>Bobi\u2019s hand tightened around the shard.</p><p>The game was almost over.</p><p>The dice rolled. The numbers came up. Kyle\u2019s settlements spread like a virus, unstoppable, inevitable. Bobi barely played now. His turns were automatic, his roads placed without thought, his attention split between the game and the tutorial, between the way Kyle\u2019s jaw held its shape on-screen and the way his own flesh yielded beneath his fingers.</p><p>He tested the river stones next, pressing one against his jaw, feeling the weight of it, the way it sat against the bone. Heavy. Solid. <em>Permanent.</em> That\u2019s what he needed. Something that wouldn\u2019t shift, wouldn\u2019t give, wouldn\u2019t let him go back to the way he was before.</p><p><em>&quot;Longest road\u2019s mine,&quot;</em> Kyle said, his cursor dragging another piece into place. <em>&quot;Ten points. Game\u2019s almost over.&quot;</em></p><p>Bobi\u2019s breath came faster. His fingers moved between the plastic and the stone, testing, measuring, imagining. The adhesive was there, too, the tube half-empty from his last attempt. He squeezed a drop onto his fingertip, feeling the chemical burn as it touched his skin. It would hold. It would <em>have</em> to hold.</p>"
