        "title": "Chapter 6: The Colonist's Architecture (9/19)",
        "content": "<p>The game was over.</p><p>Now it was his turn.</p><p>The call had ended. The screen was black. The room was his again.</p><p>Bobi exhaled, slow and controlled, the way his mother had taught him when he was a child and the village boys had chased him, calling him <em>si jelek</em>, the ugly one. <em>Breathe through the nose, anak. Hold it. Let it out slow.</em> But his nose was still swollen from the last correction, the sutures pulling with every inhale, so he breathed through his mouth instead, tasting copper and <em>Cap Tikus</em> and something older, something like the mildew in the church\u2019s back pews where the aunts had whispered about him.</p><p>The tools were laid out on the towel: the kitchen knife, its blade still streaked with dried blood from the nose; the fishing line, transparent and coiled like a sleeping snake; the tube of industrial adhesive, its nozzle crusted with yellowed glue; the plastic shards, smoothed with sandpaper, their edges sharp enough to catch the light. And the river stones\u2014three of them, flat and cool, their surfaces worn smooth by years in the current. He\u2019d found them by the bank near the <em>warung</em>, half-buried in the mud, their shapes already perfect, already <em>waiting</em>.</p><p>He uncapped the <em>Cap Tikus</em> and drank. The burn was immediate, searing down his throat, pooling in his stomach, radiating outward until his fingers stopped shaking. He drank again. The room tilted, just slightly, the fluorescent buzz softening at the edges. Good. This was good. The village anesthesia. The peasant\u2019s mercy.</p><p>He swabbed Betadine along his jawline, the brown iodine staining his skin, the scent sharp and medicinal, cutting through the smell of old blood and clove smoke. The mirror was angled just right\u2014he could see his jaw in profile, the softness of it, the way it sloped instead of cut, the way it <em>yielded</em> instead of resisted. Weak. Feminine. <em>Kampung.</em> He traced the line with his fingertip, pressing until the skin paled, until he could feel the bone beneath, the mandible\u2019s curve, the place where the plastic would go.</p><p>The YouTube tutorial was paused on the screen, the surgeon\u2019s gloved hands frozen mid-motion, the patient\u2019s face already marked with ink, the jawline a map of what was to come. Bobi had watched it six times. Seven. He knew the steps. He knew the angles. He knew where to cut.</p><p>He picked up the knife.</p><p>The first incision was a surprise.</p>"
