        "content": "<p>This time, the <em>shrit-shrit</em> was deeper, the blade meeting more resistance, the skin parting slower, the blood darker. He worked quickly, his fingers moving with a precision that surprised him, the moonshine steadying his hands, the pain a distant thing, a background hum. The stone slid into place, heavy, <em>right,</em> and he sealed it with another bead of adhesive, the burn worse this time, the scent thicker, the room spinning just slightly at the edges.</p><p>His breath came fast, shallow. The mirror was smeared with blood, his reflection fractured, his jaw already swelling, the skin stretched tight over the shards, the stone, the adhesive, the whole thing a patchwork of what he was and what he was becoming. He pressed his fingers to the skin, feeling the shapes beneath\u2014hard, unyielding, <em>there.</em> The foundation was stronger now. The scaffolding would come down. The architecture would be revealed.</p><p>The sutures were harder this time.</p><p>The jaw\u2019s incision was longer than the nose\u2019s had been, the flesh more resistant, the needle meeting more drag as it passed through. The <em>wet pop</em> came slower, the sound dampened by the thickness of the skin, the fishing line pulling tight, the stitches uneven, the tension wrong. He worked methodically, his fingers slipping on the blood, the adhesive, the sweat beading on his forehead, rolling down his temples, stinging his eyes. The thread caught on the plastic, the stone, the raw edges of the cut, snagging, resisting, until he yanked it free with a sharp tug, the pain bright and immediate, the blood welling fresh.</p><p>He didn\u2019t stop.</p><p>The line of stitches ran along his jaw like a road on a map, black and jagged, the fishing line glinting in the fluorescent light. He tied the final knot with his teeth, the thread biting into his lips, the taste of blood and plastic and something older, something like the mildew in the church\u2019s back pews where the aunts had whispered <em>si jelek.</em> He spat, red flecking the towel, and leaned back, his breath coming in short, sharp gasps, his body trembling with the effort of holding still.</p><p>The mirror showed him what he needed to see.</p><p>The jaw was swollen, the skin purple-black with bruising, the stitches pulling tight, the plastic and the stone visible beneath the surface, their shapes distorted by the flesh, the whole thing asymmetric, <em>wrong.</em> But that was just the scaffolding. That was just the <em>process.</em> The foundation was stronger now. The bone was reinforced. The architecture would reveal itself in time.</p><p>He turned to the laptop.</p><p>The webcam preview was a mercy.</p>"
