        "content": "<p>A release.</p><p>The pus erupted through the tube in a thick, yellow-green stream, warm and viscous. It splattered onto the cotton wool he\u2019d pressed against his neck, the smell hitting him immediately\u2014sweet and rotten, like overripe fruit left in the sun, like the mildew in the church\u2019s back pews after the monsoon. His stomach lurched, but he swallowed the bile back down. He couldn\u2019t afford to vomit. Not now. Not with them still there, still watching, still existing in their perfect rectangles of light.</p><p>The pus kept coming, thick and warm, pooling on the cotton wool, the color of diluted sunset. He pressed harder, his fingers slick with it, the tube digging into the abscess until the pressure eased, until the flow slowed to a trickle.</p><p>He wiped his jaw with a fresh piece of cotton wool, dabbing at the wetness, the stickiness. The skin there was raw, tender. He could feel the heat still radiating from it, the warmth of something alive and wrong.</p><p>He unmuted.</p><p>\u201cSorry,\u201d he said. \u201cBad connection.\u201d</p><p>The village laugh.</p><p>The group hadn\u2019t noticed. Of course they hadn\u2019t. The pixel was still his ally, still softening the edges, still turning the wet spot on his collar into a shadow, the swelling into a strong jawline, the infection into something ambiguous, something that could be explained away.</p><p>Julia\u2019s head tilted.</p><p>Just slightly.</p>"
