        "title": "Chapter 8: The Final Form (8/42)",
        "content": "<p>\u201cBut you were always mine,\u201d he continued. \u201cYou were always <em>torang</em>. We were always supposed to be one. The village split us. The aunts split us. The mirror split us. But not anymore.\u201d</p><p>He stood, stepping back to look at the Brother fully. The synthetic hair hung limp, dark strands matted in places, catching the dim light. The face was smooth, featureless in its perfection, the eyes wide and unblinking. The Brother didn\u2019t breathe. Didn\u2019t move. Didn\u2019t react.</p><p>Didn\u2019t <em>need</em> to.</p><p>Bobi walked to the desk. The tools were there\u2014the kitchen knife, the scissors, the fishing line, the tube of industrial adhesive. He picked up the scissors first, testing their weight in his hand. The metal was cool, the blades slightly dull from use. He set them down and picked up the knife. The edge was still sharp, still stained with the dried remnants of his last surgery. He ran his thumb along the blade, feeling the bite of it against his skin.</p><p>He turned back to the Brother.</p><p>\u201cThis isn\u2019t taking,\u201d he said. \u201cThis is <em>returning</em>. You\u2019ve always been mine. And now I\u2019m taking you back.\u201d</p><p>He began at the hairline.</p><p>His fingers found the edge of the synthetic scalp, where the dark strands met the smooth expanse of the Brother\u2019s forehead. He pressed his thumb against the material, feeling the give, the slight resistance. It wasn\u2019t skin. It wasn\u2019t flesh. It was something in between\u2014something that had been <em>shaped</em> to look like skin, to feel like skin, but wasn\u2019t quite either.</p><p>He slid the blade of the knife under the edge, separating the hair from the forehead with a slow, deliberate motion. The material resisted at first, then gave way with a sound like peeling tape\u2014wet, sticky, wrong. He worked carefully, following the curve of the forehead, the knife sliding beneath the synthetic flesh, separating it from whatever lay beneath.</p><p>The scent hit him first.</p>"
