        "title": "Chapter 8: The Final Form (9/42)",
        "content": "<p>Drying latex. Chemical adhesive. Something older, something sweet and sick beneath it, like meat left too long in the heat. His stomach tightened, but he didn\u2019t stop. He couldn\u2019t stop. This was necessary. This was <em>right</em>.</p><p>The synthetic skin came away in a single piece, a flat sheet of material that draped over his hands like a second skin. It was smooth on one side, rough on the other, the underside marked with fibers and residue, the scent of it clinging to his fingers. He laid it carefully on the bed, smoothing it out with his palms, pressing the edges flat.</p><p>The Brother\u2019s forehead was exposed now\u2014pale, mottled, not quite flesh. The material beneath was compressed, geometric, the shape of a skull but not a skull. Stuffing peeked through in places, old fabric, maybe cotton, maybe something else. Bobi didn\u2019t look too closely. He didn\u2019t need to.</p><p>He moved to the cheek.</p><p>The knife slid under the synthetic flesh again, this time meeting more resistance. The material here was thicker, the adhesive stronger. He had to press harder, the blade biting into the tacky surface, the scent of chemicals rising with each cut. The Brother\u2019s face didn\u2019t change. Didn\u2019t flinch. Didn\u2019t react.</p><p>Didn\u2019t <em>care</em>.</p><p>Bobi worked slowly, carefully, peeling the material back in strips, laying each piece on the bed beside the first. The cheek came away in two uneven sections, the edges ragged where the adhesive held fast. He smoothed them flat, his fingers pressing into the tacky underside, the fibers clinging to his skin.</p><p>The scent was stronger now.</p><p>Drying latex. Industrial glue. Something older, something <em>his</em>\u2014the copper tang of blood, the sweet-sick smell of flesh that wasn\u2019t quite right. His own flesh. The flesh he had cut from himself and given to the Brother, stitching it into the synthetic skin, the fishing line pulling it taut, the adhesive bonding it into place.</p><p>He had been building the Brother from himself all along.</p>"
