        "content": "<p>The mask lay across Bobi\u2019s palms like a second skin, cool and yielding. He turned it over, tracing the fibers with his fingertips\u2014the synthetic weave, the tacky residue of adhesive, the faint chemical scent that clung to it like a memory. The eye holes were uneven, the left slightly higher than the right, the edges frayed where he\u2019d trimmed them with the scissors. The mouth opening was too wide, the curve of it asymmetrical, but that didn\u2019t matter. Nothing mattered except the weight of it, the promise of it, the way it would finally make him whole.</p><p>He stepped toward the mirror.</p><p>The cracked glass split his reflection into two misaligned halves, the jagged line running diagonally from the top left to the bottom right, dividing him before he even began. He held the mask up to his face, aligning the eye holes with his own, the material draping over his features like a shroud. The left side of his face\u2014the side the crack favoured\u2014looked almost right. The right side was wrong, the mask\u2019s edge curling away from his skin, the adhesive not quite holding. He adjusted it, pulling the material taut, stretching it over his cheekbones, his jaw, his forehead. The fibers resisted at first, then gave, molding to the contours of his skull.</p><p>The Brother watched from the corner.</p><p>Bobi didn\u2019t look at him.</p><p>He didn\u2019t need to.</p><p>The first suture went in at the temple.</p><p>Bobi pressed the needle through the mask\u2019s edge first, the synthetic flesh parting with a sound like tearing paper. Then he angled it into his own skin, the tip breaking through the thin layer near the bone. The <em>wet pop</em> was sharper here, the resistance greater, the skin tighter after the jaw surgery, the plastic shards still shifting beneath the surface. He drew the fishing line through, the transparent thread glistening with blood as it tightened, pulling the mask flush against his temple. The material bunched slightly, the fibers catching on the stitches from the hair transplant, but he ignored it. He tied the knot\u2014double, then triple\u2014securing the first anchor point.</p><p>His hands didn\u2019t shake.</p><p>They never did when it mattered.</p>"
