        "title": "Chapter 10: The Last Livestream (15/17)",
        "content": "<p>The chair tipped. Bobi\u2019s body followed, slow at first, then all at once\u2014a deadweight collapse, his forehead striking the keyboard with a dull thud. The keys depressed under his skull, the plastic giving way to bone. The webcam feed jolted, then steadied, offering the group one final, unobstructed view: his face pressed against the keyboard, the mask\u2019s lower edge peeling back from the impact, the fishing-line sutures taut and glistening. His left eye\u2014now sewn open\u2014pressed against the <strong>space bar</strong>, the right against the <strong>M</strong> and <strong>N</strong> keys. The pressure activated them. Letters began appearing in the chat window, random and meaningless:</p><p><strong>mnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnn</strong></p><p>Klaudia\u2019s feed cut to black first. Her sobs were replaced by silence, her rectangle collapsing into a name tag: <strong>Klaudia (Offline)</strong>. Julia\u2019s camera lingered for three more seconds\u2014her face a rictus of horror, her phone clutched in one hand, the other pressed to her mouth as if she could physically hold back what she\u2019d just seen. Then her screen froze, her final expression pixelating into a blocky mask before vanishing. Kyle remained, his jaw clenched so tight the muscles feathered beneath his skin. He didn\u2019t look at the screen. His focus was on the phone pressed to his ear, his free hand slamming against his desk in rhythm with the words he barked into the receiver\u2014English first, then Cantonese, then broken Indonesian, the languages shifting as he failed to bridge the distance between Vancouver and Manado. <em>&quot;Ambulans. Sekarang. Ruang kos di Jalan Sam Ratulangi. Nomor kamar\u2014&quot;</em> His voice cracked. He didn\u2019t know the room number. He didn\u2019t know the building\u2019s name. The address was something Bobi had mentioned once, months ago, in passing. <em>&quot;Tolong. Cepat.&quot;</em> The plea dissolved into static. The emergency operator\u2019s voice was a tinny murmur, too distant to parse. Kyle\u2019s rectangle trembled as he pounded the desk again, the camera jostling with the impact.</p><p>Mina didn\u2019t move. Her beads clicked between her fingers, her lips shaping words no one in the call could understand. The prayer wasn\u2019t for Bobi. It was against what had filled the room with him, what had watched from the corner as he sewed his eyes open, what had never blinked, never spoken, never been anything but a silent witness to the dismantling. Her camera stayed on, her face illuminated by the lamp behind her, the shadows under her eyes deepening as the words spilled out, untranslated, unheard. The only sound in her rectangle was the steady, rhythmic click of the beads. The only movement was the rise and fall of her chest.</p><p>Eline\u2019s hands were pressed to the screen. Her tears had stopped falling. They hung in her lashes, refracting the lamp light into tiny, fragmented rainbows. She didn\u2019t scream. She didn\u2019t speak. She watched the gibberish fill the chat window, the endless string of <strong>m</strong>s and <strong>n</strong>s, the keyboard registering the weight of a man\u2019s forehead as if it were data. Her fingers hovered over her own keyboard, trembling. She had typed the message before she knew she was typing it. Before she could stop herself. Before she could consider what it would do to the room on the other side of the world, to the man who had already gone where messages couldn\u2019t reach.</p><p>The notification pinged.</p><p>A small, bright chime. Incongruous. Cheerful.</p><p>The chat window updated.</p><p><strong>Eline:</strong> <em>Bobi, you were always beautiful to me. Why did you do this?</em></p><p>The words appeared on Bobi\u2019s screen, just above the endless string of <strong>mnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnnn</strong>. The text was crisp, black on white, untouched by the blood smeared across the keyboard. The laptop\u2019s AI assistant\u2014enabled by default, never disabled\u2014detected the unread message. A small pop-up appeared in the corner of the screen: <strong>&quot;Read aloud?&quot;</strong> The system didn\u2019t wait for confirmation. It never had before.</p>"
