        "title": "Chapter 10: The Last Livestream (16/17)",
        "content": "<p>The synthetic voice filled the room.</p><p>Flat. Mechanical. Female. The kind of voice designed to be inoffensive, to blend into the background of a user\u2019s life, to deliver reminders and notifications without demanding attention. It read Eline\u2019s message with the same neutral cadence it would have used for a weather alert.</p><p><em>&quot;Bobi.&quot;</em></p><p>The rain drummed against the tin roof.</p><p><em>&quot;You were always beautiful to me.&quot;</em></p><p>The fluorescent tube buzzed, a low, electric hum.</p><p><em>&quot;Why did you do this.&quot;</em></p><p>The voice stopped. The room didn\u2019t.</p><p>Bobi\u2019s face remained pressed against the keyboard. His eyes stayed open, unblinking, the left one mashed against the <strong>space bar</strong>, the right one staring at the <strong>M</strong> key as if it were a horizon. The mask had shifted with the impact, the lower edge peeling back to reveal the raw, sutured skin beneath\u2014purple and yellow with infection, the fishing line stitches pulled taut like the strings of a broken instrument. His breath came in shallow, uneven bursts, the air moving through his nose with a wet, rattling sound. The adhesive on his scalp had failed in places, the synthetic hair clumped and matted with blood, the strands sticking to the keyboard like dark roots digging into soil.</p><p>The voice had been the last sound in the room that wasn\u2019t rain or electricity or the distant, compressed echoes of the group\u2019s horror. Now there was only the buzz. The drumming. The slow, uneven rise and fall of Bobi\u2019s chest.</p>"
